ce:section.ce:para:
To validate the generality and scalability of the proposed system, other reported CQDs are renamed K-CQDs and P-CQDs. They are separately confined within SBA-15 to obtain K-CQDs@SBA-15 and P-CQDs@SBA-15. The K-CQDs@SBA-15 accuracy in Cr(VI) detection is verified (Fig. 9
                        a). When the Cr(VI) concentration reaches 800 μM, the K-CQDs@SBA-15 fluorescence quenching efficiency exceeds 80 %. Linear fitting of fluorescence intensity data F0/F against Cr(VI) concentration reveals a detection limit of 0.866 μM within a concentration range of 0–100 μM (Fig. 9b), slightly lower than the reported detection limit in literature. These results suggest that K-CQDs@SBA-15 can be a fluorescence sensing platform for Cr(VI) detection. Subsequently, the P-CQDs@SBA-15 fluorescence quenching performance is examined (Fig. 9c). When the Cr(VI) concentration reaches 2000 μM, the P-CQDs@SBA-15 fluorescence quenching efficiency exceeds 80 %. Linear fitting of fluorescence intensity data F0/F against Cr(VI) concentration shows a detection limit of 0.314 μM (Fig. 9d), three times lower than the reported detection limit in the literature (Table 2
                        ). These results confirm that the synthetic strategy is universal and scalable for Cr(VI) detection.
